# handoff-to-codex

Hand off follow-up work from a Claude Code worktree session to Codex.

## Default: file-drop handoff (recommended, GUI-safe)

```bash
./scripts/handoff_to_codex.sh "describe the task for Codex here"
```

This writes a self-contained handoff (branch, commits, diff, task) to
`state/agent-inbox/for-codex.md` and prints a one-line pickup instruction.
The user then pastes that line into their live Codex session (Desktop app or TUI):

```
read state/agent-inbox/for-codex.md and proceed
```

**Why this is the default:** the Codex Desktop app renders conversations from a SQLite
store, while `codex exec` writes only to JSONL rollout files — so exec handoffs never appear
in the Desktop GUI. The file-drop path lands in the GUI because the user's *own* session reads
the file, and it has **zero effect on any other running Codex session** (no model/reasoning
overrides are sent anywhere). The optional `--ipc` path can auto-inject into a live Desktop
thread, but it remains experimental because it depends on undocumented Desktop IPC internals.

## When to use

- Claude Code has finished a feature, fix, or change in a worktree branch.
- A follow-up task is better suited for Codex: PR creation, CI triage, code review, merge,
  running external checks, or any task Codex should own.

## What to put in the task description

Git context is included automatically — be specific about what Codex should DO:

- "Create a PR for this branch targeting main. Title: [title]."
- "Review the changes in backend/app/api/reviewer_auth.py for security issues."
- "Run the test suite and fix any failures introduced by these changes."
- "Merge this branch into main once CI passes."

## Reading Codex's reply

Codex appends its result to `state/agent-inbox/for-claude.md`. Read it with the Read tool.

## Other modes

```bash
./scripts/handoff_to_codex.sh --ipc <conversationId> "task"  # auto-inject into a live Desktop GUI thread
./scripts/handoff_to_codex.sh --open [session_id]   # open a session in the terminal TUI
./scripts/handoff_to_codex.sh --app                 # open the workspace in the Codex desktop app
./scripts/handoff_to_codex.sh --exec "task" [sid]   # HEADLESS exec (NOT visible in the GUI)
```

- `--ipc <conversationId> "task"` injects the handoff straight into a live Desktop thread via the
  app's owner-gated IPC router. The owning renderer and model reply were proven on the authorized
  test thread; the user later confirmed the sent messages appeared in the Codex Windows app.
  The thread must be open in the Desktop app (its renderer must own the conversationId), else the
  router returns `no-client-found` and it **falls back to file-drop**. Model/reasoning are
  renderer-controlled: `--ipc` cannot change a thread's model/effort or affect any other session,
  and never touches `~/.codex/config.toml`. Opt-in; file-drop stays the default. Full mechanism +
  isolation evidence: `plans/2026-06-04-codex-ipc-injection.md`.
- Production `--ipc` intentionally uses `--allow-any-thread` for explicit UUID targets. Inspect the
  target session before sending; do not select targets by cwd/title/newest-thread heuristics.
- After Codex Desktop updates, run `node scripts/codex_ipc_revalidate.mjs --thread <conversationId>`
  before trusting `--ipc`. Add `--allow-live-ipc-read` only to re-prove read-only router
  `initialize`; it does not send a prompt.
- If a new Desktop thread exists but its id is unknown, use
  `node scripts/codex_ipc_thread_locator.mjs --project <project> --limit 10` to discover candidates,
  then inspect the selected id before sending.
- For a static contract audit, run `node scripts/codex_ipc_contract_audit.mjs`; it reads repo
  artifacts only and emits a requirement matrix.
- `--open` / `--app` are for taking over a session interactively.
- `--exec` runs `codex exec resume` headlessly and saves Codex's reply to `for-claude.md`.
  Use it only for fire-and-forget tasks where you read the reply file. It does **not** appear
  in the Desktop GUI (by design — see the architecture note above). Its `-m` / `-c` flags are
  per-invocation and never modify `~/.codex/config.toml` or affect other sessions.

## Cross-session context inspection

Each handoff carries pointers so either agent can investigate the other's **full session
transcript** (not just the message), when needed.

**Codex → Claude (both file-drop and `--ipc`):** every `for-codex.md` handoff includes a
"Claude session context" block with Claude's session id and the absolute path (Windows form) to
Claude's transcript JSONL (`~/.claude/projects/<mangled-project>/<session-id>.jsonl`). Codex can
read it under its sandbox (empirically verified — it read the transcript's first line). It is
large; grep/tail for the relevant part, and it may contain unrelated context.

**Claude → Codex:**
- `--ipc <conversationId>`: the conversationId **is** the Codex rollout session id. Read Codex's
  full transcript at `~/.codex/sessions/<YYYY>/<MM>/<DD>/rollout-*-<conversationId>.jsonl`.
- file-drop: Codex usually cannot self-report its session id from inside a turn, so locate its
  rollout by searching `~/.codex/sessions/` for this handoff's content/markers (or ask which
  session picked it up).

## Optional env

```bash
CLAUDE_SESSION_ID=<uuid>       # override the Claude session id advertised in the handoff
CLAUDE_TRANSCRIPT=<path>       # override the Claude transcript path advertised in the handoff
CODEX_SESSION_ID=<uuid>        # --exec / --open: target a specific session (positional arg wins)
CODEX_REASONING_EFFORT=xhigh   # file-drop: advisory note in the handoff; --exec: per-invocation pin
```

## Troubleshooting

- **Handoff not visible in the Desktop app** — Confirm you pasted the pickup line into the
  session and that the session's working directory is this workspace. The file-drop itself only
  writes `for-codex.md`; the GUI turn happens when your session reads it.
- **"'codex' not found on PATH"** — Only `--open` / `--app` / `--exec` need the Codex CLI; the
  default file-drop does not.
- **Worktree-safe** — All modes resolve the main workspace via `git worktree list`, so they work
  from any worktree subdirectory.
